title: For Sale:  1869 Ballard
postcontent: This is an Original 1869 single shot Ballard that has been cut down by an American Indian to create a "blanket or canoe gun". Native Americans were known to cut down the long guns found at the trading post to create and easier handling carbine lenght weapon. This one was found poorly cut and had to be recut by only a few inches. The gun is an original and will come with a reproduction brochure, with history and drawing of the parts. This gun will need a new spring to make the hammer work. I would suggest that if you choose to shoot this gun you should have is completely checked out by a gunsmith. Seller is selling this gun as a relic that will not be shot so shoot it at your own risk. title: For Sale:  Echo AR-II Drop In Trigger For The AR-15 Rifle
postcontent: The Echo Trigger allows the shooter to select from 3 different settings  Safe Mode: Firearm will not fire. Semi-Automatic Mode: Firearm fires when trigger is pulled. Echo Mode: Firearm fires when trigger is pulled and also when trigger is released.  The Echo Trigger is designed with safety being the utmost priority. When the shooter is in the Echo Mode and depresses the trigger one round is fired, if the target moves, the shooter can move the selector to the safe position and a second round will not fire upon release. The echo trigger has several distinct features  PATENTED Design that gained ATF Approval (Patent # US 8,820,211 B1) Technology licensed through HIPERFIRE inside the Echo Trigger Light, clean, and crisp pull in Semi-Automatic Mode The Echo Trigger is packed full of cutting edge technology Reliable function in Echo Mode

title: For Sale:  Miniature Colt 45
location: N St Pete, Tampa/St. Pete, Florida
postcontent: Manufactured by the American Miniature Gun Mfg. Co. of Hollywood, California, and marketed as the Frontier "45".  On much of it's literature it was also referred to as the "Little 45".  A difficult to classify miniature, although modeled after the Colt Frontier Single Action revolver, it is not a true miniature of that gun.  The Frontier "45" is a six shot, single action, revolver with a hand rotated barrel (cylinder).  At 3 1/2″ OAL, this little beauty is much nicer than a toy, but not quite a true miniature.  Manufactured in the 1950's it has more detail, and is more functional than the best of the toy miniatures.  It's cylinder rotates.  It has full and half cock.  It has a flip down side loading gate, and fires brass, percussion cap-like ammunition.  Expended shells are ejected with a functioning spring loaded ejector, just like on the real thing.  It is unusual in that the complete trigger guard acts as its trigger and is pulled back to fire.  This part is delicate and many of these guns are found with the tab that holds the trigger assembly in place broken.  The clean finish on these guns suggest that they are sturdy little pieces.  They were however, cast in a pot metal.  It is the care that was taken in finishing these guns that makes them look more substantial than they actually are. This is a popular gun with collectors and a relatively difficult gun to find.  Prices are considerably higher than for even the best of the toy miniatures such as Armodelli or Hubley guns."These sets sold for $27.50 back in the late 1950's, which was a large sum to pay for a toy.  This example is serial number 4012.  The set is in mint condition, the trigger is still functional as is the loading gate, another piece that is often broken or missing.  The nickel finish retains 100% original nickle plating.  The two piece pearl grips with a single screw entering from the left side are excellent with no cracks or chips. The original case is walnut, has a slide latch, and a rectangular plaque mounted to the case top by two small brass nails.  The case is in nice condition.  The interior bottom of the case French fit and lined in a dark burgundy velour.  It is rare to find one of these complete and in this kind of condition.This one has an authentic 45 cartridge instead of the plastic one it usually comes with and intials on plaque.$400 OBO.

It's in fantastic shape, and the serial number dates it to 1990 and is one of the rarer ones that's marked Heckler & Koch on the side of the receiver. What's unique about this gun is that you can run it in BOTH semi auto and pump action because of its unique design, and that allows you to run anything from blanks to full power 3" magnum buckshot with no hiccups.
